course: Rolling 10 mile loop with fair to good pavement.
registration:
Pre-Register at www.sportsbaseonline.com. 2nd race is $10.00. Day of registration opens at 7:00 AM and closes 15 minutes prior to race. Day of race registration add $7.00 late fee. Waivers must be signed at registration prior to each race. Minimum field of 10 entrants. NO REFUNDS AFTER MARCH 13 AT 12:01 AM!!!
For further information contact Steve Stuart at 510-552-0291 or stuball52@sbcglobal.net.
notes: Prizes 100% cash!!. Race held rain or shine. Races held rain or shine and held under USA Cycling permit. 2009 license required, day and annual licenses are available at registration. Fees include NCNCA and USA Cycling insurance charges.
directions:
From San Francisco take I-80 east to I-505 north. Exit at County Road 14. Immediate right on County Road 90A. Before 8 AM turn left on County Road 16 to parking. After 8 AM go straight just past CR 16 to parking on west shoulder of 90A. 
From Sacramento take I-5 north to Zamora exit. Go west on County Road 13 (becomes County Road 14) to County Road 90A. Please do not take County Road 92B as the race is on this narrow road. Left on 90A to County Road 16 parking before 8 AM or to parking on 90A south of 16 after 8 AM. Use caution on County Road 13 and 90A as racers are using one lane of these roads.

title: 2010 SCNCA Elite, Masters & Juniors Time Trial Cha
For A Fist Full Of Handlebars
2010 Mountain Bike Races at Loma Rica Ranch
Scotts Valley Grand Prix

address.street: 200 El Pueblo Drive, Scotts Valley, CA 95066

description: One of the newest races on the NCNCA calendar, the Scotts Valley Grand Prix is going to light up the Twilight Sky of the Santa Cruz Mountains. It will bring top-level bike racing to one of the golden spots of Northern California with speed, power, adrenaline, and insane fun.
course:
A one mile (1.6km) circuit in the business district of Scotts Valley which runs clockwise on the streets El Pueblo Drive, Carbonero Way, and Scotts Valley Drive with full road closure. 

The road surface is good and the course features long straights, three turns, and one chicane toward the start/finish. 

The Start/Finish is 300m north of the corner of 200 El Pueblo Drive and Carbonero Way between the Seagate parking lots.
registration:
Held Under USA Cycling permit # 2010-860 • USAC license required and must present a current USA Cycling license at registration • Annual license also available day of race • No phone or faxed entries will be accepted • Race promoter reserves right to deny entry to any athlete per promoter’s discretion • All participants will sign a waiver/release form at registration • Riders must wear a helmet that meets USA Cycling requirements. Registration fee includes $3 USAC insurance surcharge and $1 NCNCA surcharge. Entry fee does not include on-line registration fee • Day of race registration add an additional $7.00

Register online: <http://www.truesport.com/register/events/flyer.asp?ID=1200> • Pre-registration closes 5/13/2010 7:00PM PST
On-site Registration: Opens at 2:00pm, closes 
30 minutes before each race. If entering two races, second race is 1/2 price.
notes: All eligible divisions will be counted toward NCNCA BAR and BAT rankings. Neutral Support provided.
directions:
Directions:
From San Jose take CA-17S Exit 5
•	Head southwest on Exit 5 toward Scotts Valley Dr - go 0.2 mi
•	Turn left at Scotts Valley Dr - go 1.2 mi
•	Make a U-turn at Civic Center Drive and follow signs to course parking
	Total: 1.7 mi - about 5 mins

From Santa Cruz take CA-17 N
•	take exit 3 for Mt Hermon Rd - go 0.1 mi
•	Turn right at Mt Hermon Rd - go 0.4 mi
•	Take the 3rd light onto Scotts Valley Dr - go 0.8 mi
•	Pass Civic Center Drive intersection and follow signs to course parking

Parking available south of course and some areas on the northbound straight (Scotts Valley Drive)
Registration will be south of course near parking area.
Cyclists Village near the Start/Finish reserved for professional competitors that pre-register - click here for details

title: Big Creek Lumber Criterium at Castle
San Rafael Twilight Criterium
description: On July 11th, the speed and adrenaline of professional cycling returns to the streets of San Rafael. Prepare yourself for the pageantry of the criterium style of racing -- short, fast, urban and gritty. Absorb the romanticism of a twilight race -- part fading sun, part Downtown Lights. This isn’t cycling you watch. This is cycling you feel.
course: The 1-km course, located in San Rafael’s vibrant downtown setting, starts and finishes on 4th Street while running clockwise on 4th, E St., 5th St., and B St. The Expo will occupy 4th St. between A St. & B St., while the Pro Athlete Village area is located between Lootens and A St. (Note: A St., west/east bound access will remain open to through traffic).
registration: All fields are limited and will sell-out. Please register early. No phone or faxed entries will be accepted. Race promoter reserves right to deny entry to any athlete per promoter’s discretion. • All participants will sign a waiver/release form at registration. Those under 18 years old require a parent\'s or guardian\'s signature. •	USA Cycling sanctioned. Riders must present a current USA Cycling license at registration. •	Competitor age is determined by the age of the rider on Dec. 31, 2010.  Extra Race is $20.  There are no refunds or transfers.
notes: Neutral Technical support will be provided by SRAM.
directions: From US-101, take the Central San Rafael Exit, merge onto Irwin and make a left on 3rd St. The closed course is between Lootens & E St on 4th St.

title: USAC Upgrade Points & Resume Builder Crit Series
Marin Classic-USAC Develop Foundation Fund Raiser
2010 USA Cycling Collegiate MTB Nationals
description:
The 2010 Collegiate Mountain Bike National Championships are being held at the picturesque Northstar at Tahoe™ Resort on October 15 - 17, 2010.

The best collegiate mountain bike athletes will descend upon the largest bike park in Northern California for three intense days of racing. Come on out and cheer for your favorite college or university team as they race hard all weekend to bring the glory home to their school!
directions:
From the Bay + Sacramento Areas:
• Go East on Interstate 80 for roughly 3 hours (184 miles). 
• From Sacramento, roughly 1 hour 45 minutes (103 miles).
• Take Highway 267 Exit #188B. This is the new by-pass route. It is just after the last Truckee Exit
• Turn Right onto Highway 267
• Continue on Highway 267 for approx 6 miles through Martis Valley
• Turn Right onto Northstar Dr.
• See \"After Turning onto Northstar Dr.\" 	

From Reno:
• Go West on Interstate 80 for roughly 30 minutes (30 miles)
• Take the Northstar Exit #188, Highway 267
• Turn Left onto Highway 267
• Continue on Highway 267 for approx 6 miles through Martis Valley
• Turn Right onto Northstar Dr.
• See \"After Turning onto Northstar Dr.\"

After Turning onto Northstar Dr.:
Make an immediate right for Northstar Resort Lodging check in, or continue straight on Northstar Dr. to the Village at Northstar for resort services, access to the mountain, and lodging check in for our alternative lodging options.
